          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> is called <html:em><html:strong>total</html:strong></html:em> whenever its <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KB.xml" title="domain of definition of a partial function" addr="jms-00KB" type="local">domain of definition</fr:link> coincides with its domain (source), i.e. we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>. In this case, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and refer to it as a <html:em><html:strong>function</html:strong></html:em> or a <html:em><html:strong>map</html:strong></html:em>. Sometimes, we redundantly refer to it as a <html:em><html:strong>total function</html:strong></html:em>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Just as we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Rel}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>for the sets of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relations</fr:link> and <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial functions</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> respectively, we shall write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\to  B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the set of functions from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
